# {{PROJECT_NAME}} — SDLC Flow

**Status:** Living document
**Last updated:** {{TODAY}}

This is the development lifecycle for {{PROJECT_NAME}}: how a task travels from an idea to
merged code. The shape is deliberate — the **spec is authored in `main`**, then the rest of
the pipeline runs **autonomously inside a sandbox**, and the **only human touchpoint is a
single review just before the final commit**, when there is a working prototype to look at.

> This is the current default flow. As the project matures, additional flows (different
> autonomy levels) will live next to this file under `sdlc/`.

---

## The flow

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    subgraph main1["main repo"]
        spec["spec-creator<br/>writes the spec"]
    end

    spawn(["⎇ spawn sandbox<br/>branch sandbox/&lt;name&gt;"])

    subgraph sandbox["sandbox · all of this runs here"]
        direction LR
        subgraph devloop["development loop"]
            direction LR
            designer["designer<br/>UI/UX only"]
            plan["plan-creator<br/>writes the plan"]
            arev["architect<br/>review the plan"]
            dev["developer<br/>implement"]
            test["tester<br/>tests vs acceptance criteria"]
            adoc["architect<br/>update technical docs"]
            designer --> plan --> arev --> dev --> test --> adoc
        end
        review{"human review<br/>artifacts + working prototype"}
        commit(["final commit"])
        adoc --> review
        review -- "approved" --> commit
        review -- "changes" --> devloop
    end

    subgraph main2["main repo"]
        merge(["merge → main<br/>delete sandbox"])
    end

    spec --> spawn --> designer
    commit --> merge
```

The diagram reads left to right. Only `spec-creator` runs in `main`. Inside the sandbox the
agents form an autonomous **development loop**; its output goes to a single **human review**,
which either sends changes **back into the loop** (at whatever step they touch) or approves
— and only then is the **final commit** made. Everything except the final merge happens
inside the sandbox.

---

## The boundary: `main` vs sandbox

| Stage | Where it runs | Produces |
|---|---|---|
| spec-creator | **main** | `specs/<task>-spec.md` |
| designer (UI/UX only) | sandbox | `specs/<task>-design.md` + `design/mockups/<task>/` |
| plan-creator | sandbox | `specs/<task>-plan.md` |
| architect (review) | sandbox | verdict on the plan; ADR entry if needed |
| developer | sandbox | the implementation on the sandbox branch |
| tester | sandbox | tests + per-AC report |
| architect (update) | sandbox | updated `architecture/architecture.md` |
| human review | sandbox | approval, or change requests that re-run earlier steps |
| final commit | sandbox | the committed deliverable on the sandbox branch |
| merge + delete sandbox | **main** | the merged result on `main` |

The spec is the contract handed into the sandbox. Everything the sandbox produces stays on
its branch until you merge — so `main` only ever sees reviewed, working results.

---

## Sandbox lifecycle

1. **Spawn.** After the spec is written, create a sandbox on a fresh branch
   (`sandbox/<name>`). The recommended tool is **`agent-sandbox`** — its VS Code task **Spawn
   Agent Sandbox** clones the repo into `agent-sandboxes/<name>/`, branches, and opens an
   isolated dev container. **It is not required**: a manual `git clone` + branch, or a remote
   agent
   (e.g. `claude --remote`), works just as well. The flow only assumes "an isolated branch
   you can throw away."
2. **Run.** The agents execute the pipeline above autonomously inside the sandbox, ending
   with a working prototype and all artifacts on the sandbox branch.
3. **Review.** You open the finished sandbox and review the **working prototype** plus the
   artifacts (spec, design, mockups, plan, tests, updated architecture). Reviewing a running
   prototype is far easier than reviewing a plan on paper.
4. **Finalize & merge.** Once you're convinced, the **final commit** is made and the sandbox
   branch is merged into `main` (agent-sandbox: **Merge Agent Sandbox**). If you wanted
   changes instead, the agents re-run on the same branch (see below) and you review again —
   nothing is committed as final until you're satisfied.
5. **Delete.** Tear the sandbox down (**Remove Agent Sandbox**). It was always disposable.

---

## The agents, in order

- **spec-creator** — the WHAT/WHY, in `main`, before the sandbox exists.
- **designer** — UX/UI thinking for user-facing tasks: surfaces, flows, states, and HTML
  mockups. Skipped for backend/CLI-only tasks.
- **plan-creator** — the HOW: file-level changes, reuse, verification steps.
- **architect (review)** — gates the plan against `architecture/architecture.md`.
- **developer** — implements the approved plan on the sandbox branch.
- **tester** — maps every acceptance criterion to a test and runs them.
- **architect (update)** — distills what changed back into `architecture/architecture.md`.

The architect appears twice: once to **review the plan**, once to **update the docs** from
the final changes.

---

## Review & merge

There are no approval gates mid-pipeline. The review happens **once**, against a finished,
running result, and **before the final commit** — there's no point committing, reviewing,
then committing again:

- If it's good → **final commit** → merge → delete the sandbox.
- If it needs changes → it goes **back into the development loop**, re-entering at whatever
  step the feedback touches (not necessarily back at the designer), on the **same branch** —
  the sandbox isn't thrown away until you're satisfied — then you review again.

This is the single intentional human-in-the-loop point. Future flow variants may move,
remove, or add to it.

---

## Without a sandbox (fallback)

The sandbox is a convenience, not a hard dependency. The same pipeline runs directly in the
repo, as long as task work happens on a **dedicated branch** rather than `main`:

- If the developer finds itself on `main`, it creates a working branch (`task/<task-slug>`)
  before making any change.
- You review the branch and merge it the usual way.

The only thing the flow insists on is: **`main` never receives unreviewed task work.**

---

## Future: variant flows

Because the pipeline already runs autonomously inside a sandbox, flows can be composed at
different **autonomy levels** — for example a stricter flow that adds an explicit pre-merge
gate, or a fully unattended flow that merges on green tests with no human review. Each such
variant will be its own file under `sdlc/`, with this document as the default.
